Pour 300ml cold salted @water{} into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.
Stir in the @chicken stock{1%sachet} and @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove from the heat. Keep covered for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve 
(the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, place your hand flat on top of the @Irish chicken breast{320%g} and 
slice through horizontally to make two thin steaks.

Toss the sliced chicken with @paprika{2%sachets}, @salt{to taste} and 
@pepper{to taste}.

> Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal 
> due to packaging we use to keep it fresh. It will still taste delicious once 
> cooked!

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, add the chicken and season with salt and pepper. Fry until browned, 
~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

> TIP: Cook in batches if your pan is getting crowded.

Once the chicken has browned, add the @cherry tomatoes{125%g} to the pan.

Fry until chicken is cooked through and tomatoes are softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the tomatoes have softened, use the back of a #spoon{} to carefully burst 
the tomatoes and release the juices.

Add a knob of @butter{to taste} to the pan along with the @tomato paste{1%tin}, 
stirring together to create a buttery tomato sauce.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the @peas{120%g}.

> TIP: Loosen with a splash of water if necessary!

Divide the peas and rice between #bowls{}.

Top with the fried chicken steaks and buttery tomatoes.

Drizzle with @aioli{1%sachet} and @sweet chilli sauce{1%sachet}.